Health Insurance and Temporary Incapacity Coverage

This circular provides a summary of the Agreement signed between the OSCE and Vanbreda International (Vanbreda) with regard to health insurance and temporary incapacity coverage for OSCE employees. It also provides information on procedures for enrolment in insurance coverage and on submission of claims to insurance company.
This Staff Circular, cancelling and superseding Staff Circular 01/2001 and its Annexes issued on 1 March 2006, becomes effective on January 1, 2008.

Health coverage applies on a compulsory basis to all OSCE officials and interns, and their dependants (for fixed-term staff/mission members), unless they are covered by an alternative social security scheme recognized by the OSCE.
This coverage applies on compulsory basis for the fixed-term contracted staff /mission members enrolled in VB health coverage (categories 01, 02, 08).

Fixed-term contracted staff members in Vienna, covered under their national social security scheme to which the OSCE contributes, may also opt for participation in the Supplementary health insurance scheme provided by Vanbreda.  The OSCE shall not contribute to the cost of those premiums.

In case of travel outside the mission area emergency medical treatment in the country of occurrence would be covered.

For local mission members in other OSCE Missions coverage is limited to the mission area. In case of travel outside the mission area emergency medical treatment in the country of occurrence would be covered.
The insurance is suspended in time of war for any insured person(s) who is (are) mobilized or who volunteer for military service.

In order to be enrolled to VB scheme or to be allowed to continue participation in their own scheme, OSCE officials shall fill in Health Insurance Request Form (Annex 4).

In case of an emergency hospitalisation, staff/mission members should inform either the Personnel/Administrative Officer in their Institution/Mission or Vanbreda directly (telephone number:
+ 32 3 2176963) as soon as possible and at the latest before discharge from the hospital. Hospitalisation form (Annex 5) should be sent to Vanbreda by fax (+323 663 28 10).

In case of non-emergency hospitalisation (including outpatient treatment), staff/mission members should inform Vanbreda at least three weeks in advance using the attached pre-certification form (Annex 6).  They have to provide mandatory diagnosis, specification of the required medical treatment, address/Tel/fax of the hospital where the treatment will be given, expected duration of the hospitalisation and expected cost of the treatment.  Failure to comply with the pre-certification requirement will result in a 10% reduction on the reimbursement rate.

As the costs of hospitalisation are generally high, Vanbreda can arrange for direct payment of all costs to the hospital and the staff/mission member will have to pay only the difference between the costs reimbursed by Vanbreda and the full costs of hospitalisation.  In case of any assistance needed in this respect, staff/mission members may contact either Personnel/Administrative Officer in their Institution/Mission or Vanbreda directly for obtaining, if necessary, a letter of guarantee from Vanbreda.
12. EXTENSION OF COVERAGE UPON SEPARATION FROM THE OSCE

Contracted fixed-term staff/mission members may opt to extend their health insurance coverage with Vanbreda for a period of six months after their separation from the OSCE provided that both the OSCE and Vanbreda have been duly informed prior to the date of separation from the OSCE (please contact your Chief of Fund Administration or Personnel Officer ).  The corresponding premiums are to be paid in advance for the whole extended period required. Staff/mission member shall pay both Organisation and Staff shares of premium.

Seconded fixed-term staff/mission members may opt to extend their health insurance coverage with Vanbreda for a period of six months after their separation from the OSCE provided that both the OSCE and Vanbreda have been duly informed prior to the date of separation from the OSCE (please contact your Chief of Fund Administration or Personnel Officer ). Extension is subject to the following conditions:
At least one year of continuous service prior to separation from the OSCE;
Participation in Vanbreda health insurance scheme during the same period;
The corresponding premiums are to be paid in advance for the whole extended period required.
Distribution:  All staff/mission members of the OSCE

SUMMARY OF COVERAGE UNDER TEMPORARY INCAPACITY INSURANCE SCHEME

A staff member recognized by a doctor, jointly designated by the OSCE and by the insurers, as being temporarily incapable to exercise his/her responsibilities will, after a continuous and total interruption of two months, receive an indemnity.

The indemnity will be equal to 80% of the monthly salary. The remaining 20% of the salary will continue to be covered by the OSCE up to the exhaustion of certified sick leave entitlements on full pay, as per Staff Rule 7.05.02. When entitlement to certified sick leave on full pay is exhausted, fixed-term staff and mission members will continue to receive 80% of salary, paid by Vanbreda International.

The payment of the indemnity will be continued until (i) the date the staff member is capable of resuming work; (ii) until the date he/she is recognized as permanently disabled; (iii) until the end of the month during which the staff member reaches his/her 65th birth date, or (iv) until the moment of death.  In any case, the period of payment relating to the same illness or accident cannot exceed two years.

When the temporary incapacity becomes partial, staff members will receive a reduced indemnity, but the degree of partial incapacity should always be at least 50%. For example, someone in full incapacity receives 80% of monthly salary; someone returning to work at 80% receives no indemnity since degree of incapacity is 20% which is less than 50%; someone returning to work at 50% receives 40% of the salary, which is 50% of 80%.

When a staff member, having benefited from these indemnities but not having reached the two year maximum limit, relapses within a period of two months after resuming his/her functions, the period during which the staff member has temporarily resumed his/her functions, will only cause a suspension of the benefits and the payment of the indemnities will be continued without a new waiting period.

HOW TO SUBMIT CLAIMS FOR REIMBURSEMENT OF MEDICAL EXPENSES
Vanbreda forms can be found on VB website under Members Access/Forms:

It is strongly recommended to use the forms available on this website, as they facilitate the processing of claims. They are intended for your personal use only, as your name, personal reference number and the corresponding bar code automatically appear on some of them.

The costs incurred should be grouped according to the nature of the services provided.  Treatments that have been paid but not yet undergone cannot be reimbursed. A separate claim form for each insured person needs to be completed. Insured spouse and child(ren) shall submit their claims through the insured staff/mission members, and not directly to Vanbreda. The currency in which the medical expenses have been incurred should be indicated.
Staff/mission members may wish to keep copies of the receipts and the form for their own records.

Staff/mission members with full coverage must submit original bills and prescriptions, accompanied by receipts of payment.  Staff having supplementary coverage should first submit all bills to their National health insurance scheme.  When completing the form, those staff should state the amount reimbursed by the National health insurance scheme. In the event that the National health insurance scheme refuses to reimburse the amount, a written statement from either the insurer or the staff member explaining the reason for the refusal must be attached to the claim.  In case the national insurer retains the original, photocopies may be submitted to Vanbreda.
A diagnosis and date of treatment must be given on every physician's bill.

Claims for reimbursement of the cost of spectacles or contact lenses, if covered by the terms of insurance policy, must be accompanied by the optician's invoice, listing separately the dioptres and cost of each lens (frames are excluded from reimbursement).

For medicines or drugs purchased from a pharmacy the original prescriptions from the medical practitioner must also be submitted.  Pharmacy receipts are not accepted in lieu of prescriptions unless local law requires the pharmacy to retain the original prescription, in which case an explanatory note or a photocopy of the prescription should accompany the claim.
Bills for dental treatment must be itemized (because of the limitations on certain types of treatment) and show exact date of treatment(s).

Claims will be reimbursed by the insurer in Euro either by cheque or to the bank account of the staff/mission member.  In case of a bank transfer, the name of the bank and the full account number (including IBAN and SWIFT code) should be indicated on the claim form.  Staff/mission members are responsible for payment of bank charges (Bank charges are only payable when the bank is outside the EUR zone). It is therefore advisable to group invoices for medical services.

Any conversion of expenses incurred in another currency will normally be made on the basis of the OSCE official exchange rate in force on the date the reimbursement is effected.  Differences resulting from exchange rate fluctuations are the responsibility of the staff member.

If a staff/mission member opts to be reimbursed by cheque, a crossed cheque will be mailed to the staff/mission member which may only be cleared against a personal bank account of the cheque recipient.

In view of banking difficulties in some of the countries where the OSCE has its operations and relatively small amounts of medical expenses incurred in that countries, reimbursements can be received via the OSCE mission bank account (the reimbursement will be made to the mission member with the payment of his/her salary ).

A claim shall be paid by Vanbreda only if it is submitted by the staff/mission member within two years from the date of the event giving rise to the claim, provided that the coverage was valid at that time.
Vanbreda settlement notes will be sent via e-mail or letter to staff/mission member or can be checked on-line under Members Access/Settlement Details.

Staff/mission members, who require additional information or clarification regarding their claims, or a letter of guarantee in case of hospitalization, may contact directly Vanbredas claims department dealing with the OSCE health insurance plan, tel. + 32 3 217 69 63, fax + 32 3 663 28 10. Postal address: Postbox 69, 2140 Antwerpen, Belgium. E-mail: mcc103@vanbreda.com
The annual limit is pro-rated in case period of coverage differs from the calendar year.
The percentage will be lowered by 10% in case of non-emergency hospitalisation if the pre-certification procedure is not followed.

In case hospital applies all-inclusive price without breaking it down to doctors fees and other expenses, Vanbreda will apply the following split: Bed and Board-40%;Other hospital expenses-40%, Doctors fees- 20%  For example, if all-inclusive bill equals to 100,00 Eur, VB will treat 40 EUR as Bed and Board (rate do reimbursement 100%), another 40 EUR as  Other hospital expenses (rate do reimbursement 100%), and 20 EUR as doctors fee (rate of reimbursement 80%). Total amount of reimbursement would be 96 EUR.

Surgeries which are performed under local anaesthesia and do not require the use of an operating hall-even if one is used-can as well be done in a doctors office and are therefore reimbursed as medical care at 80%.
